Section 9 of the Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996, deals with interim measures by a court. It states that a party may, before or during arbitral proceedings or at any time after the making of the arbitral award but before it is enforced, apply to a court for an interim measure of protection. 

The court may grant the following interim measures:
- to preserve the subject-matter of the dispute;
- to take interim custody of the subject-matter of the dispute or to take steps to preserve evidence;
- to provide for the sale of perishable goods;
- to secure the amount in dispute;
- to restrain a party from transferring or disposing of assets;
- to restrain a party from alienating assets;
- to grant any other interim measure of protection as may appear to the court to be just and convenient.

(Section 9, Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996)

Under Section 31 of the Specific Relief Act, 1963, a written instrument can be cancelled if it is unlawful or useless, or if it has been obtained by misrepresentation, fraud, or coercion. The court may cancel a written instrument in the following circumstances:

1. The instrument is unlawful (Section 31(a));
2. The instrument is useless (Section 31(b));
3. The instrument was obtained by misrepresentation, fraud, or coercion (Section 31(c));
4. The instrument is voidable under Section 19 or Section 19-A of the Indian Contract Act, 1872 (Section 31(d));
5. The instrument is a decree or order obtained by fraud or coercion (Section 31(e)).

The court may cancel the instrument on a suit by any person against whom the instrument is voidable or who is entitled to have it declared void. (Section 31, Specific Relief Act, 1963)

Under Section 6 of the Transfer of Property Act, 1882, the following kinds of property cannot be transferred:

1. The interest of a lessee under a lease of immovable property (Section 6(a));
2. The interest of a tenant for life (Section 6(b));
3. The interest of a kharif or other cultivator of land (Section 6(c));
4. Any easement (Section 6(d));
5. A mere right to sue (Section 6(e));
6. A public office (Section 6(f));
7. A public trust (Section 6(g));
8. Stipends allowed to military, naval, air-force and civil pensioners of Government and political pensions (Section 6(h)).

Under Section 2(68) of the Companies Act, 2013, a private company is defined as a company that has a minimum paid-up share capital of one lakh rupees or such higher paid-up share capital as may be prescribed, and which by its articles—

(a) restricts the right to transfer its shares;
(b) except in the case of One Person Company, limits the number of its members to two hundred;
(c) prohibits any invitation to the public to subscribe for any securities of the company; and
(d) prohibits any invitation or acceptance of deposits from persons other than its members, directors or their relatives.

Under Section 164 of the Companies Act, 2013, a person shall not be eligible to be appointed as a director of a company if he-

1. is of unsound mind and stands so declared by a competent court (Section 164(1)(a));
2. is an undischarged insolvent (Section 164(1)(b));
3. has applied to be adjudicated as an insolvent and his application is pending (Section 164(1)(c));
4. has been convicted by a court of any offense, whether involving moral turpitude or otherwise, and sentenced to imprisonment for not less than six months, and a period of five years has not elapsed from the date of expiry of the sentence (Section 164(1)(d));
5. has not paid any calls in respect of any shares of the company held by him, whether alone or jointly with others, and six months have elapsed from the last day fixed for the payment of the call (Section 164(1)(e));
6. has been convicted of the offense dealing with related party transactions under Section 188 of the Companies Act at any time during the last preceding five years (Section 164(2)). 

Additionally, a private company may have its own disqualifications for directors as per its Articles of Association.

Under Section 9 of the Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996, a party can seek interim measures from the court before, during, or after the arbitration proceedings. These measures include:

1. Appointment of a guardian for a minor or person of unsound mind (Section 9(1)(a));
2. Preservation, interim custody, or sale of any goods which are the subject-matter of the arbitration agreement (Section 9(1)(b));
3. Securing the amount in dispute in the arbitration (Section 9(1)(c));
4. Detention, preservation, or inspection of any property or thing which is the subject-matter of the arbitration agreement (Section 9(1)(d));
5. Interim injunction or the appointment of a receiver (Section 9(1)(e));
6. Such other interim measure of protection as may appear to the court to be just and convenient (Section 9(1)(f)).

The court may grant these interim measures to prevent any of the parties from being prejudiced or to protect the subject-matter of the dispute. (Section 9, Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996)

Under Section 37 of the Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996, the following orders are appealable:

1. Refusing to refer the parties to arbitration under Section 8 (Order refusing reference to arbitration);
2. Granting or refusing to grant any interim measure under Section 9 (Interim measures by Court);
3. Refusing to enforce a foreign award under Section 36 (Enforcement of foreign awards), after the award has been recognized by the Court;
4. Setting aside or refusing to set aside an arbitral award under Section 34 (Application for setting aside arbitral award).

These orders can be appealed to the Court as per Section 37 of the Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996.

Under Section 19 of the Protection of Women from Domestic Violence Act, 2005, the following residence orders are available:

1. Restraining the respondent from dispossessing or in any other manner disturbing the possession of the shared household (Section 19(a));
2. Directing the respondent to remove himself from the shared household (Section 19(b));
3. Restraining the respondent or any of his relatives from entering any portion of the shared household in which the petitioner resides (Section 19(c));
4. Restraining the respondent from alienating any assets in the shared household which are jointly or singly owned by the respondent (Section 19(d)).
